Hantavirus - Texas (new case) 950628
ProMED: Re: Hantavirus -- Texas 950629
[1
Date: Tue, 20 Jun 2000 11:49:48 -0400
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: Scripps Howard News Service, 20 Jun 2000 [edited

Colorado health officials are investigating whether an Adams County woman
may have contracted [a hantavirus infection at her home. State
epidemiologist John Pape said he would not be surprised if the woman did
contract the sometimes deadly disease at her rural home. "If you live in a
rural area anywhere in Colorado, potentially you have exposure risks," Pape
said. The 54-year-old woman, whose name was not released, was in critical
condition Monday at St. Joseph Hospital in Denver. She was admitted last
Wednesday with typical, flu-like symptoms that accompany the disease, Pape
said.
Pape said the investigation into where the woman contracted the disease is
ongoing. She had been in other parts of rural Colorado and Utah in the past
6 weeks - within the incubation period. But Pape said the woman was hiking
and recreating while away from her home. [Hantaviral infections in the
southwestern U.S. typically [are contracted when people clean out sheds
or barns [where infected rodents have left their droppings.
Pape said it is unclear what activities the woman may have been doing at
her home if she contracted [the hantavirus there. Last year, a Loveland,
Colorado area man became the first person along the Front Range [the
eastern side of the Rocky Mountains to contract [a hantavirus infection.
He survived.
The Adams County woman is the 5th reported case in Colorado this year. Two
people have died.
[If I can determine what investigations are being done by the state, I will
pass on that information. - Mod.CHC
